# Polynomial Fit Plot
age.grid = seq(min(Wage$age), max(Wage$age))
lm.fit = lm(wage ~ poly(age, 2), data=Wage)
preds = predict(lm.fit, data.frame(age=age.grid), se=TRUE)
se.bands = cbind(preds$fit + 2 * preds$se.fit, preds$fit - 2 * preds$se.fit)
plot(wage ~ age, data = Wage, col = "darkgrey", xlab = "Age", ylab = "Wage", main="Polynomial Fit")
lines(age.grid, preds$fit, col="blue", lwd=2)
matlines(age.grid, se.bands, lwd = 1, col = "black", lty = 3)


The ANOVA test would allow us to use models with the highest polynomials of degree 2, 3 and 9 with a significance level of 5%. However, if we choose a level of significance of 1%, we would only be abble to use the model with the polynomial of degree 2, since this is the only one with a significance level below 1%.
Given the 1 Standard Deviation Rule (choose the simplest model within 1 standard deviation from the model with the best result), the polynomial of degree 2 was chosen.

b) K-fold cross-validation on Wage (step function):

set.seed(1)
cv.error.10 = c()
for (i in 2:10) {
  Wage$age.cut = cut(Wage$age, i)
  lm.fit = glm(wage ~ age.cut, data = Wage)
  cv.error.10[i] = cv.glm(Wage, lm.fit, K=10)$delta[2]
}
cv.error.10
##  [1]       NA 1733.849 1683.181 1638.865 1631.087 1622.854 1611.697
##  [8] 1600.299 1611.174 1605.175

Plots the results:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
minimum = min(cv.error.10, na.rm = T)
sdKfold = sd(cv.error.10, na.rm = T)

# Cross-Validation Plot
plot(2:10, cv.error.10[2:10], xlab="Number of Steps", ylab="Cross-Validation Error", type="l", pch=20, lwd=2, ylim=c(1590, 1750), col="blue", main = "10-fold CV")
abline(h = minimum + sdKfold, col="red", lty="dashed")
points(x = which.min(cv.error.10), y = minimum, pch=19)

# Step Function Fit Plot
lm.fit = glm(wage~cut(age, 4), data=Wage)
age.grid = seq(min(Wage$age), max(Wage$age))
preds = predict(lm.fit, data.frame(age=age.grid), se=TRUE)
se.bands = cbind(preds$fit + 2 * preds$se.fit, preds$fit - 2 * preds$se.fit)
plot(wage~age, data=Wage, col="darkgrey", xlab = "Age", ylab = "Wage", main = c("Step Function Fit:", "4 Steps"))
lines(age.grid, preds$fit, col="blue", lwd=2)
matlines(age.grid, se.bands, lwd = 1, col = "black", lty = 3)


Again, the optimal number of cuts was chosen using the 1 Standard Deviation Rule. Looking at the graph, it seems like there are only 3 steps, but checking for the steps we can see why:

unique(preds$fit)
## [1]  94.15839 118.21188 117.82295 101.79898
minimum + sdKfold
## [1] 1644.195
cv.error.10[3:4]
## [1] 1683.181 1638.865

This happened because the fit at the third cut is very similar to the fit at the second cut.Yet the model with 3 Steps has a Cross-Validation error that is higher than the minimum cross validation error obtained plus one standard deviation. For this reason, the model with 3 steps was discarded.

Step Regression

I’ll analyze the variable Year to see if it’s relation with Wage can be explained in a satisfactory manner by a step regression:
Let’s use cross-validation to choose the most adequate number of steps:

set.seed(1)
cv.error.10 = c()
for (i in 1:7) {
  if (i == 1) {
    lm.fit = glm(wage ~ year, data = Wage)
  } else {
    Wage$year.cut = cut(Wage$year, i)
    lm.fit = glm(wage ~ year.cut, data = Wage)
  }
  cv.error.10[i] = cv.glm(Wage, lm.fit, K=10)$delta[2]
}
cv.error.10
## [1] 1734.410 1738.861 1738.530 1739.655 1739.694 1742.041 1738.625

Plots the results:

minimum = min(cv.error.10, na.rm = T)
sdKfold = sd(cv.error.10, na.rm = T)

# Cross-Validation Plot
plot(1:7, cv.error.10[1:7], xlab="Number of Steps", ylab="Cross-Validation Error", type="l", pch=20, lwd=2, ylim=c(1730, 1745), col="blue", main = "10-fold CV")
abline(h = minimum + sdKfold, col="red", lty="dashed")
abline(h = minimum - sdKfold, col="red", lty="dashed")
points(x = which.min(cv.error.10), y = minimum, pch=19)


The Cross-Validation results shows that a linear model represents more accurately the relation between Year and Wage. For this reason, we won’t analyze this data with a step function.

Looking at the relation between mpg and the others variables, the graphs suggest that we could fit some non-linear models using the variables displacement, horsepower, weight, acceleration and year. We’ll test this claim by fitting some non-linear models using these variables:

par(mfrow = c(2,3))
# Displacement
set.seed(1)
cv.error.10 = c()
for(i in 1:10){
  if(i == 1){
    lm.fit = glm(mpg ~ displacement, data = Auto) 
  } else {
    Auto$displacement.cut = cut(Auto$displacement, i)
    lm.fit = glm(mpg ~ displacement.cut, data = Auto)
  }
  cv.error.10[i] = cv.glm(Auto, lm.fit, K = 10)$delta[2]
}
minimum = min(cv.error.10)
sdKfold = sd(cv.error.10)

# Cross-Validation Plot
plot(1:10, cv.error.10, xlab="Number of Steps", ylab="Cross-Validation Error", type="l", pch=20, lwd=2, col="blue", main = "Displacement")
abline(h = minimum + sdKfold, col="red", lty="dashed")
points(x = which.min(cv.error.10), y = minimum, pch=19)

The cross-validation error plots shows that althought the best fit for all the variables has more than one step, a linear model would still be a good model to measure the relation between mpg and these variables. The only exception would be the variable year. For this variable we can see that the simplest model that would give us a good fit is a step regression with 4 steps.

lm.fit = glm(mpg~cut(year, 4), data=Auto)
year.grid = seq(min(Auto$year), max(Auto$year))
preds = predict(lm.fit, data.frame(year=year.grid))
plot(mpg~year, data=Auto, col="darkgrey", xlab = "Year", ylab = "mpg", main = c("Step Regression:", "Year with 4 Steps"))
lines(year.grid, preds, col="blue", lwd=2)

set.seed(1)
x1 = rnorm(100, 3, 2)
x2 = rnorm(100, -7, 4)
y = 0.7 + 3 * x1 - 5 * x2 + rnorm(100)


b)

beta1 = 10


c)

a = y - beta1 * x1
beta2 = lm(a~x2)$coef[2]


d)

a = y - beta2 * x2
beta1 = lm(a~x1)$coef[2]


e & f)

b0 = c()
b1 = c()
b2 = c()
a = 0
for(i in 1:1000){
  a = y - beta1 * x1
  beta2 = lm(a~x2)$coef[2]
  a = y - beta2 * x2
  beta1 = lm(a~x1)$coef[2]
  b0[i] = lm(y ~ x1 + x2)$coef[1]
  b1[i] = beta1
  b2[i] = beta2
}
plot(1:1000, b0, xlab = "Iteractions", ylab = "Estimated value", type = "l", lwd = 2, ylim = c(-7, 15), col = "blue", main = expression("Estimates for B"[0]*", B"[1]*" and B"[2]))
lines(1:1000, b1, col = "purple", lwd = 2)
lines(1:1000, b2, col = "red", lwd = 2)

fit = lm(y ~ x1 + x2)
multib0 = coef(fit)[1]
multib1 = coef(fit)[2]
multib2 = coef(fit)[3]
abline(h = multib0, lty = 3, lwd = 3)
abline(h = multib1, lty = 3, lwd = 3)
abline(h = multib2, lty = 3, lwd = 3)

# Legend
legend("topright", c(expression("B"[0]), expression("B"[1]), expression("B"[2]), "Multiple OLS estimates"), lty = c(1,1,1,3), lwd = c(2,2,2,3), col = c("blue", "purple", "red", "black"), cex = 0.9)


The graph shows that the coefficients obtained for \(B_0\), \(B_1\) and \(B_2\) through iteractions and through a multivariate regression are the same - We can also see that iteractive method generates coefficients that converge pretty quickly to the coefficients obtained in a multivariate linear model.

g) Since we were working with a linear model, a single iteration was enough to make the coefficients converge to the coefficients of a multiple regression.
